e="data"><ref type="bibliography"\r\n                                        target="bibliography.php#JRWORKSLE">Ruskin, <hi\r\n                                            rend="italic">Works</hi></ref>, 2:350&#x2013;51</cell>\r\n                            </row>\r\n                            <row role="data">\r\n                                <cell n="1" role="data"></cell>\r\n                                <cell n="1" role="data"></cell>\r\n                                <cell n="1" role="data"></cell>\r\n                                <cell n="1" role="data"></cell>\r\n                                <cell n="1" role="data" xml:id="HEIDELBERG1"><ref type="witness" target="heidelberg_poem1_msviii.php">&#x201C;Smiling from those bright rays kiss&#x201D; [&#x201C;Heidelberg&#x201D;] [poem, part 1]</ref></cell>\r\n                                <cell n="1" role="data">939&#x2013;68</cell>\r\n                                <cell n="1" role="data" corresp="MOSTBEAUTIFULARETHEPATHS">to come</cell>\r\n                                \r\n                                <cell n="1" role="data">\r\n                                    <ref type="witness"\r\n                                        target="most_beautiful_are_the_paths_msix.php">&#x201C;Most\r\n                                        beautiful are the paths&#x201D;</ref>(poem)</cell>\r\n                                <cell n="1" role="data">to come</cell>\r\n                                <cell n="1" role="data"><ref type="bibliography"\r\n                                        target="bibliography.php#JRWORKSLE">Ruskin, <hi\r\n                                            rend="italic">Works</hi></ref>, 2:361&#x2013;62. In n. 1\r\n                                    on p. 361, the editors print what they represent as draft lines\r\n                                    in <ref type="apparatus" target="msviii_apparatus.php">MS VIII</ref>, dropped from\r\n                                    the <ref type="witness" target="account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_msix.php">MS IX</ref>. The reverse is\r\n                                    true, however; these lines are not found in <ref type="apparatus" target="msviii_apparatus.php">MS VIII</ref>, but in \r\n                                    <ref type="witness" target="account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_msix.php">MS IX</ref>. In other words, if the reader restores the\r\n                                    lines in n. 1 to their place where annotated by the editors, the\r\n                                    poem reads as it appears in fair copy, \r\n                                    <ref type="witness" target="account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_msix.php">MS IX</ref>. When\r\n                                    one makes this correction to the text as edited in the Library\r\n                                    Edition, the 30 lines comprising <ref type="witness"\r\n                                        target="smiling_from_those_bright_rays_kiss_msviii.php"\r\n                                        >&#x201C;Smiling from those bright rays kiss&#x201D;</ref>\r\n                                    can be recognized as draft for lines 19&#x2013;48 of the fair\r\n                                    copy&#x2014;counting, that is, the lines that the editors\r\n                                    inexplicably drop into a note on p. 361.</cell>\r\n                            </row>\r\n                            <row role="data">\r\n                                <cell n="1" role="data"></cell>\r\n                                <cell n="1" role="data"></cell>\r\n                                <cell n="1" role="data"></cell>\r\n                                <cell n="1" role="data"></cell>\r\n                                <cell n="1" role="data" xml:id="TRADITIONSOFTHERHINE"><ref type="witness" target="the_traditions_of_the_rhine_prose_msviii.php">&#x201C;The traditions of the Rhine&#x201D; [&#x201C;The Rhine&#x201D;] 